b.font: Event Stream Processing and State Management

div.font: Depending on software design, this could look like many things, but the idea is always the same: observe events & change state.

div.div: Clicks, taps, keystrokes, voice commands or what-have-you will all trigger events over time while the application process is running.

div.style: display: flex; align-items: unsafe center; justify-content: unsafe center; width: 208px; height: 1px; padding-top: 275px; margin-left: 11px;
box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 0px; text-align: center;
display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; pointer-events: all; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal;

div.div: Application "state" and how it's managed is entirely context dependent, but is generally defined as "operational memory". JS variables, DOM properties, URL params, and local storage are common locations of "state" in FE web systems.

div.style: display: flex; align-items: unsafe center; justify-content: unsafe center; width: 168px; height: 1px; padding-top: 745px; margin-left: 301px;

div.div: "Events" are context dependent, but generally define some type of occurrence in the system, along with any data used to describe it to the event processor.
